<TEXT>
geoffrey palmer selected as new 
zealands new prime minister has a reputation as an academic he 
also is a fan of country and western music and a man who knows the 
united states from up close 
palmer 47 took office as head of the governing labor party on 
tuesday following the surprise resignation of laborite david lange 
as prime minister the previous day party leadership assures 
palmers election in parliament as prime minister 
palmer with frizzled silver hair thunderous voice and 
earnestness is known within the labor party as moses 
he will take over as prime minister 10 years after entering 
parliament in a special election 
a former law professor he is from the centerright of the party 
and has been the driving force behind the governments legal 
initiatives including a proposed bill of rights 
palmer is not a socialist despite having reached the top of a 
party that is proud of its socialist traditions palmer says he is 
a middleoftheroader on economic issues neither a free marketeer 
nor a centralist 
colleagues say he has selfconfidence and loves arguing former 
students remember him as a demanding teacher 
he collects royal albert bone china as a hobby and plays the 
trumpet 
palmer is not expected to strive for the limelight on the world 
stage in the same manner as lange 
he rarely shows his boisterous element of humor in public but 
friends say its there he was once in a group of university 
pranksters taken to a police station for breaking into a womens 
hostel 
long periods of living overseas helped mold the political 
palmer at his first news conference tuesday after his election as 
party leader he said he was very fond of the united states 
having spent so much time there 
when he and his wife margaret went to chicago in the 1960s 
they expressed shock at the violence and squalor they lived with 
their baby son on the south side slept on a mattress on the floor 
and drove a 50 car that was not insured because they could not 
foot the bill 
they returned to the united states in 1969 when palmer was 
appointed professor of law at iowa university he later moved to 
another professorship at virginia 
palmer has said he came to love the united states for its human 
diversity and lively intellectual culture 
at his news conference palmer said the governments course 
would be solid and dependable but perhaps not exciting he said 
there would be no change in economic policy and that finance 
minister david caygill would remain in his job even though his 
predecessor roger douglas was back in the cabinet 
he also declared himself a staunch supporter of new zealands 
stand against visits by nuclear ships and said there would 
definitely be no change in the policy 
</TEXT>
