division but those were hardly the ideological battles of the 
former president reagans era 
on minimum wage democrats could not override bushs veto they 
then failed to paint him as being meanspirited on the issue 
because unlike reagan bushs position wasnt extreme opposition 
but simply supporting a smaller increase than the democrats 
preferred 
the house democratic leadership attempted to make a class issue 
of bushs support of a capital gains tax cut but conservatives in 
their own party have sided with the white house 
politically murkier still for the leadership was bushs threat 
last week to veto his huge savings and loan bailout plan if it 
contained a democratic plan for financing the scheme bush won 
concessions as democrats couldnt muster vetooverride strength 
the house has shredded bushs defense budget and voted to ease 
abortion spending rules for the district of columbia but new veto 
threats could reverse those outcomes 
michael robinson a professor of government at georgetown 
