<TEXT>
an obscure law nearly 200 years old will be 
pivotal in deciding civil lawsuits accusing former philippine 
president ferdinand marcos of instituting a reign of terror in his 
homeland lawyers for both sides say 
the attorneys debated sunday whether deposed dictators should be 
held responsible in american courts for human rights abuses 
allegedly committed in their homelands the discussion was part of 
the american bar associations convention here 
last month the us 9th circuit court of appeals reinstated 
damage suits accusing marcos of ordering the imprisonment and 
torture of numerous philippine citizens during his 20year rule 
the suits had been dismissed by us district courts in hawaii 
and california on the grounds that marcos alleged actions were 
acts of state immune from lawsuit under a doctrine that courts 
in one nation cannot judge the sovreign acts of another 
we feel these suits are the only way the victims will be 
able to obtain justice said sherry broder a honolulu attorney 
representing the alleged victims 
obviously the victims couldnt seek justice in the 
philippines during marcos rule and now that hes here this is 
the proper place to file she said 
richard hibey a washingtonbased marcos attorney said the 
circuit court ruling would be appealed to the us supreme court 
he contends the united states has no jurisdiction in the case and 
that marcos still holds immunity as a head of state despite his 
ouster in february 1986 during a civilianmilitary revolt 
these cases do not belong here they are not the judicial 
business of the united states said hibey what you have here 
is aliens suing aliens not one of the acts was alleged to have 
occurred in the united states 
however jon van dyke a law professor at the university of 
hawaii and broders cocounsel said international law holds that 
government officials cannot mistreat their people and if they 
do they can be sued wherever they can be found 
van dyke and broder said an alien tort statute enacted in 1790 
set the precedent for one foreigner to sue another in the united 
states and would be used to prove marcos was liable 
however hibey said the statute was based on an altercation 
between two frenchmen in the united states and therefore was 
irrelevant in the marcos case in which the alleged abuse occurred 
in the philippines he said the law would help him prove that the 
cases against marcos should be heard in the philippines 
hibey said the us solicitor generals office had filed an 
amicus brief agreeing that marcos should not be sued in the united 
states for civil cases he called that significant because there 
is virtually nothing the united states and i agree on in respect to 
these marcos cases 
last october the us government indicted the 71yearold 
marcos and his wife imelda on criminal racketeering charges 
accusing him of stealing more than 100 million from the philippine 
treasury and stashing it in the united states 
marcos has been separated from the case because of respiratory 
heart and kidney problems that have kept him hospitalized since 
jan 15 he remained in critical condition sunday at st francis 
medical center where he remains on lifesupport equipment a 
hospital spokeswoman said 
