about 400000 people fled to rooftops 
and makeshift bamboo shelters today in northern bangladesh as new 
floods killed nine people relief ministry officials and news 
reports said 
the death toll for the past two weeks of flooding stood at 164 
according to newspaper reports the governments body count stood 
at 30 but officials usually are slow in releasing death figures 
because of lengthy bureaucratic procedures 
the worst affected area was sylhet district where tens of 
thousands of mud and straw houses were destroyed according to the 
relief ministry officials who spoke on condition of anonymity 
new floods hit 30 villages in the area on sunday killing six 
men and three children and marooning 100000 others the annual 
deluge had already stranded about 300000 people across a 
400squaremile area 
lack of transportation is hampering relief work said one 
relief ministry official two helipads that had been built in the 
area for relief operations were under 2 feet of water and roads 
and telecommunications were cut he said 
officials said the most severely hit region was the teagrowing 
zakiganj area in sylhet district 120 miles northeast of dhaka 
they said at least 10 people had died of diarrhea in zakiganj 
during the last five days at least 1000 others were affected by 
the illness which is caused by impure drinking water 
last summer more than 1400 people died in floods that submerged 
threefourths of this country of 110 million people 
