us and soviet negotiators today ended the first 
talks on cutting longrange nuclear forces since president bush 
took office and a soviet representative said they failed to bridge 
major disagreements 
soviet chief envoy yuri nazarkin said the sevenweek session 
made progress on some technical points however he added 
whatever progress has been made does not involve to my regret 
solutions to major outstanding issues 
responding to a bush administration proposal nazarkin said 
testing anticheating measures before a treaty is complete could 
be helpful he said moscow is reviewing the proposal 
the 4yearold negotiations which include spacebased missile 
defenses will resume sept 25 after a sept 1920 meeting between 
secretary of state james a baker iii and soviet foreign minister 
eduard shevardnadze in the united states they are expected to 
discuss arms control 
both sides have acknowledged that full agreement on a strategic 
arms reduction treaty is not in sight 
a major dispute from the beginning has centered on us plans 
for spacebased missile defenses known as the strategic defense 
initiative or star wars moscow links a treaty to what washington 
considers crippling restrictions on such a system 
disagreement also persists on longrange nuclear crise missiles 
based at sea moscow wants to include them under the treatys 
limits washington refuses saying their presence cannot be 
monitored reliably progress was reported on monitoring provisions 
for mobile missiles but the sides still disagree on whether they 
should be allowed at all the united states wants to ban the 
weapons which it does not have the soviets who have such 
missiles reject a ban 
however many details of an agreement have already been worked 
out including mutual limits of 6000 nuclear warheads 
the draft treaty covers nuclear forces with ranges above 3400 
miles including intercontinental missiles and heavy bombers 
