the weather outlook improved greatly 
today as a blackedout countdown advanced toward a tuesday launch 
of space shuttle columbia on a mission to put a spy satellite into 
orbit 
the mission will be columbias first flight in 3 years during 
which nasas oldest shuttle was used for spare parts 
forecasters said there was only a 5 percent chance of 
unfavorable weather interfering with the launch that was down from 
sundays prediction of 20 percent to 40 percent based on the 
possibility of clouds lingering in the area 
its looking very good said capt ken warren an air force 
spokesman 
the five astronauts received briefings on launch preparations as 
sources reported the countdown today entered a planned 17hour 
hold a period reserved for catching up on any lagging work the 
sources reported there was little catchup to do 
because the mission is classified the pentagon will permit nasa 
to say only that liftoff will occur between 730 am and 1130 
am tuesday 
the space agency will make the countdown public just nine 
minutes before launch and will provide only three brief 
announcements during the fiveday mission on the spacecrafts 
condition and on the landing time at edwards air force base in 
california 
the defense department has determined that the longer we can 
keep the launch time and the type of payload under wraps the less 
chance anyone has of tracking it and learning what it is warren 
said 
published reports and sources who requested anonymity have said 
the astronauts will put into orbit a sophisticated satellite to 
gather intelligence over the soviet union china the middle east 
and other areas of military interest 
