central america policy 
mexicos perceived role as one of the staunchest supporters in 
the hemisphere of nicaraguas leftist government and the rebel 
movement in el salvador embittered officials of the reagan 
administration 
with the almost simultaneous advent of the bush and salinas 
admininistrations central america has faded as an issue and there 
is a sense in washington that mexico is far more serious now about 
confronting drug smugglers 
baker acknowledged that the united states bears part of the 
blame for the drug problem because of the senseless demand for 
drugs a statement that reflects a longheld mexican view 
mexico has been a principal source of heroin and marijuana and a 
transit point for usbound cocaine shipments mexican officials 
believe a reduction in us demand is the most effective means of 
combating the problem 
nonetheless baker said salinas has taken decisive action on the 
drug issue mexicos success over the past six months in 
capturing and prosecuting drug traffickers has seized the worlds 
attention 
