<TEXT>
as many as 30 commodity traders indicted in a 
federal probe of chicagos futures exchanges eventually will plead 
guilty according to a published report 
attorneys for some of the 46 traders indicted last week said 
guilty pleas could come as early as wednesday when 21 defendants 
who traded in the japanese yen pit at the chicago mercantile 
exchange are scheduled to be arraigned the chicago tribune 
reported in todays editions 
it was thought last week that 14 traders would plead guilty 
rather than face trial the tribune said it raised its estimate 
over the weekend after interviewing defense lawyers 
the charges range from prearranged trading to racketeering 
conspiracy and tax fraud most of the charges involve schemes in 
which traders allegedly pocketed part of the profit from trades 
they made for customers while passing on to customers their 
personal losses 
the defendants traded in the yen and swiss franc pits at the 
merc and the soybean and us treasury bond pits at the chicago 
board of trade 
attorneys said decisions to plead guilty by some traders were 
based on three considerations government evidence against the 
traders the potentially heavy prison sentences and fines for a 
conviction on racketeering charges and new federal sentencing 
guidelines that remove much judicial discretion 
