<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration on monday 
canceled a 79 million contract with hazeltine corp to bring a new 
generation of landing systems to the nations airports 
the faa said in a statement that production delays have put the 
program three years behind schedule but the agency remains 
committed to using the new microwave landing systems at major us 
airports in 1998 and at all airports around the year 2000 
hazeltine has delivered two of the 178 landing systems called 
for in the contract since beginning work in 1984 one has been 
installed at the lebanon nh airport 
the agency said it would buy 26 systems from other sources test 
that equipment and a decision on how to move ahead will depend 
upon successful completion of the evaluation program the faa 
said it plans to award a new contract in 1991 
a spokesman for hazeltines parent company emerson electric 
corp said the company plans to file suit contesting the decision 
the spokesman said problems including payments and timing of 
deliveries were the result of changes the faa made in the contract 
after it was awarded 
the contract changes required by the faa over several years 
are so numerous and substantial that they have fundementally 
altered the nature and the cost of the contract said the 
spokesman who asked that his name not be used 
the system uses highfrequency microwaves to direct planes to 
landings allowing them to make curved and steeper approaches 
outside the strict paths necessary under the current instrument 
landing system virtually immune to weather the system can 
increase an airports flight capacity and helps planes avoid 
residential areas 
air carriers have been reluctant to support the microwave 
system saying it isnt much better than the current system 
the faa in june warned that hazeltines contract was in danger 
of being canceled because of production problems hazeltine had 
said the price of the contract was too low and entered an 
unauthorized work slowdown last august dick arnold head of the 
faas microwave landing system program said in june 
the company was given a delay in a decision on the contract in 
july to see if it could find another firm to it over but no such 
contractor was found according to the faa 
the agency had been planning on putting new microwave systems at 
the laconia and manchester airports in new hampshire but faa 
spokesman john leyden has said that because of the delays it may 
put early systems at highprofile highvolume airports such as 
john f kennedy international in new york 
the faa plans to buy 750 of the new systems if congress 
approves 
</TEXT>
